{{Korean name|[[Baek|Baik]]}}
{{Infobox Korean name
| hangul = 백봉
| hanja  = 白峰
| mr     = Paek Pong
| rr     = Baek Bong
}}

'''Baik Bong''' ({{korean|hangul=백봉|context=north}}) is a North Korean author known for writing the official biography of [[Kim Il-sung]].

==Biography of Kim Il-sung==
The first comprehensive biography of Kim Il-sung was published in Korean in North Korea in 1968. It was called ''Minjogŭi t'aeyang Kim Il-sŏng changgun'' (''Sun of the People, General Kim Il-sung''). Although it was most likely written by a collective, it appeared under the name of Baik Bong.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=150}} Before that, hagiography of Kim Il-sung had been identified with [[Han Sorya]], but after he was purged, hagiography conventionally no longer appeared under the name of any one author.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=149}} Baik's biography was published by the party in two volumes. It covered Kim Il-sung's life up to the end of 1967.<ref name="ScalapinoLee1972">{{cite book|author1=Robert A. Scalapino|author2=Chong-Sik Lee|title=Communism in Korea: The society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g2M_yhsWc6gC&pg=PA1439|year=1972|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-02274-4|page=1439}}</ref>

A new version was Baik's biography was published in August 1972 as ''Ilyu haebang ŭi kusŏng Kim Il-sŏng wŏnsu'' (''Marshal Kim Il-sung, Liberator of Mankind''), prompted by the fact that the nascent ''[[Juche]]'' ideology had been attributed to Kim Il-sung from his youth, which had to be written into the story.{{sfn|Myers|2015|p=124}}

A three-volume biography followed. The biography recounts his successes in the fight for national independence. During the 1960s and 1970s, [[P'yŏngyang]] began a massive campaign to publish the works and feats of Kim Il-sung in several languages in order to promote its ''[[Juche]]'' ideology throughout the world (and in the third world in particular). The first volume is titled "From Birth to Triumphant Return to Homeland," the second volume "From Building Democratic Korea to Chollima Flight," and the third volume "From Independent National Economy to 10-Point Political Programme."<ref Name="Martin">{{cite book  | last =Martin  | first =Bradley K.   | title =Under the Loving Care of the Fatherly Leader: North Korea and the Kim Dynasty  | publisher = St. Martin's Griffin  | date= 2004  | location = | pages =754  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=PYJcbheEVBEC&pg=PA754  | doi = |ISBN = 0-312-32221-6 }}</ref> It has since become "the standard DPRK biography" of Kim Il-sung.<ref name="Buzo1999">{{cite book|last=Buzo|first=Adrian|title=The Guerilla Dynasty: Politics and Leadership in North Korea|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6T5XT9O42sC&pg=PA249|year=1999|publisher=I.B.Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1-86064-415-3|page=2n1}}</ref>

===Factual accuracy===
Baik devoted much of his work in the official biography to recount Kim Il-sung's struggle against the Japanese occupiers. Factual accuracy of many such anti-Japanese tales has been questioned.<ref>{{cite book|title=Korea & World Affairs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4T9DAAAAYAAJ|year=1981|publisher=Research Center for Peace and Unification.|page=187}}</ref>{{sfn|Yi|1979|p=67}} Baik also omits any mention of Kim Il-sung's association with the [[Northeastern People's Revolutionary Army]].{{sfn|Yi|1979|p=75}} It has also been suggested that "Baik Bong" is a pseudonym and that the writer lives in Japan.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=150}}

