'''Malcolm Scarth Isbister''' (August 31, 1850 &ndash; June 30, 1920<ref>{{cite web |url=http://speedy.scs.sk.ca/saskatoon100/students/crosswords/PDF%20SUpport%20Docs/chronology.pdf |title=Saskatoon Chronology: 1882-2005 |last=O'Brien |first=Jeff |publisher=City of Saskatoon |date=July 2005 |accessdate=2009-08-23}}</ref>) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]]-born merchant and political figure in [[Saskatchewan]], Canada. He served as mayor of [[Saskatoon, Saskatchewan|Saskatoon]] in 1905.<ref name=bio>{{cite web |url=http://www.saskatoon.ca/DEPARTMENTS/City%20Clerks%20Office/City%20Archives/City%20History/Documents/Saskatoon-City-Council_April-23-2014.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140623141055/http://www.saskatoon.ca/DEPARTMENTS/City%20Clerks%20Office/City%20Archives/City%20History/Documents/Saskatoon-City-Council_April-23-2014.pdf|archivedate=June 23, 2014|publisher=City of Saskatoon |title=A Seat on Council: The Aldermen, Councillors and Mayors of Saskatoon 1903-2006 |last=Pedersen |first=Jen}}</ref>

He was born in the [[Orkney Islands]], the son of John Isbister, and came to [[Galt, Ontario|Galt]], [[Canada West]] with his parents in 1857. Isbister was educated in [[Huron County, Ontario|Huron County]] and at the [[normal school]] in [[Toronto]]. He taught school in Ontario for a number of years. In 1874, Isbister married Margaret Sharpe.

He worked as a contractor for the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] in 1883, then entered business as the junior partner with his brother Adam Isbister in [[Petrolia, Ontario|Petrolia]] and [[Port Arthur, Ontario|Port Arthur]] where they purchased the stock and goodwill of merchant Noah Keen Street in November 1884. The firm assigned to its creditors after the death of Adam Isbister in March 1890.<ref>''Weekly Herald and Lake Superior Miner'', 22 Nov. 1884; ''Daily Sentinel'', 31 March, 11 April 1890.</ref> Isbister operated a hotel in [[Souris, Manitoba]] from 1892 to 1894 and then in [[Wawanesa, Manitoba|Wawanesa]] from 1897 to 1903. He then moved to Saskatoon, where he opened a hardware business. Isbister served as town [[coroner]], postmaster and as a member of the board of governors for the Saskatoon City Hospital. He was also president of the Board of Trade for several years.<ref name="who">{{cite book |url=http://www.ourroots.ca/e/toc.aspx?id=3121 |title=Who's who in western Canada |publisher=Canadian Press Association |year=1911 |page=219 |accessdate=2009-08-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615061913/http://www.ourroots.ca/e/toc.aspx?id=3121 |archivedate=2011-06-15 |df= }}</ref>

