{{Paranormal}}
{{italic title}} '''''Saved by the Light''''' ([[Villard (imprint)|Villard Books]], 1994, [[Harper Torch]] 1995 {{ISBN|0-06-100889-3}}) is a book by Dannion Brinkley purportedly describing his purported [[near-death experience]] (NDE). It is co-authored by [[Paul Perry (author)|Paul Perry]]. Brinkley claims to have been struck by lightning and to have clinically died for approximately twenty-eight minutes. He eventually told a tale of a dark tunnel, a crystal city, and a "cathedral of knowledge" where thirteen "angels" shared with him over a hundred revelations about the future, some of which he claims have come true.
Some of the book's major assertions have been challenged, including claims of how long Brinkley was supposedly dead, and details of his recovery.
== Refutations == Some of the book's assertions were subsequently challenged, including claims of where and how Brinkley recovered and how long he was supposedly dead,<ref name=exposed/> and claims made about his military service record.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-03-24/news/ls-46593_1_death-experience|title=Blinded by the Light? : Tales of near-death experiences--from visions of God to meeting Elvis--fascinate millions of us. But as the stories increase, so does the criticism.|last=Rivernburg|first=Roy|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=1995-03-24|accessdate=2016-03-25}}</ref><ref name=Stolen>B. G. Burkett and Glenna Whitley, ''Stolen Valor: How the Vietnam generation was robbed of its heroes and its history'', pp. 385–387. Verity Press, 1998. {{ISBN|0-9667036-0-X}}.</ref><ref name=RevDeath>Excerpt from {{YouTube|b4BeWRddAjc|"Reverend Death"}}, June 25, 2008, produced by www.WorldofWonder.net and aired on Britain's Channel 4</ref> Interviews with his physician and the reporter who interviewed him indicate that Brinkley never entered the hospital or morgue and that Brinkley originally did not claim to have died, but only that he "was out for a few minutes", and that his wife saved his life.<ref name=exposed>{{YouTube|b4BeWRddAjc|"Dannion Brinkley Exposed"}}</ref> This is in sharp contrast to the story of a morgue-revival after being dead for 28 minutes as was claimed in the book.
== Commercial success == Within two weeks of publication, another 5000 copies were printed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-03-24/news/vw-37786_1_sherwin-b-nuland|title='How We Die' Becomes Surprise Hit|last=Colford|first=Paul D.|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=1994-03-24|accessdate=2016-03-25}}</ref> The book was on ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} bestseller charts for over 25 weeks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-27183906.html|title=Incredible Journey Author's near-death experience brings an enlightened view of life|last=Kelly|first=Leslie|work=[[The Spokesman-Review]]|date=1995-01-23|accessdate=2016-03-25}}</ref>
The book was adapted for a 1995 [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] TV film [[Saved by the Light (film)|of the same name]] starring [[Eric Roberts]]. Since originally airing, it has been in regular circulation on the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] television network.
